ðŸ“– **Description:**
    The `dd` command is used to copy and convert files. It is a powerful utility that can be used for backing up data, cloning disks, and converting file formats.

âš™ï¸ **Options:**
    ðŸ”¹ `dd if=FILE`   -->  ðŸ“¥  Specifies the input file or device to copy from. If you want to copy from a device, specify the device name instead of a file.
    ðŸ”¹ `dd of=FILE`   -->  ðŸ“¤  Specifies the output file or device to copy to. If you want to write to a device, specify the device name.
    ðŸ”¹ `dd bs=SIZE`   -->  ðŸ“¦  Sets the block size for copying. A larger block size can improve performance. For example, `bs=4M` means a block size of 4 megabytes.
    ðŸ”¹ `dd count=NUMBER` -->  ðŸ”¢  Specifies the number of blocks to copy.
    ðŸ”¹ `dd conv=MODE`   -->  ðŸ”„  Specifies conversion options to apply to the data. For example, `conv=sync` adds padding bytes to ensure complete blocks.

ðŸ›  **Examples:**

    $ dd if=/dev/sda of=disk.img bs=4M
    
